AUDIENCE: One
question I would have

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:39.700
for you is if you could
explain to us some

00:44:39.700 --> 00:44:41.030
of the difference
between a designation

00:44:41.030 --> 00:44:43.120
of a national monument
versus a national park

00:44:43.120 --> 00:44:45.203
and some of the other
possibilities the government

00:44:45.203 --> 00:44:47.570
had with these lands,
that would be awesome.

00:44:47.570 --> 00:44:48.450
DAVID LAMFROM: So I
think everybody knows

00:44:48.450 --> 00:44:49.533
that government is simple.

00:44:56.160 --> 00:44:58.720
There's so many different
agencies in the California

00:44:58.720 --> 00:45:00.510
desert that manage land.

00:45:00.510 --> 00:45:05.610
So there's different-- within
the Interior Department,

00:45:05.610 --> 00:45:07.906
and within that
Interior Department,

00:45:07.906 --> 00:45:09.780
there is the Bureau of
Land Management, which

00:45:09.780 --> 00:45:13.520
is the largest landowner
in the entire country.

00:45:13.520 --> 00:45:16.130
And they manage for
a specific purpose,

00:45:16.130 --> 00:45:19.090
which is called multiple
use, which means

00:45:19.090 --> 00:45:20.540
that they protect some lands.

00:45:20.540 --> 00:45:22.790
Some lands are designated
for protection.

00:45:22.790 --> 00:45:28.790
Some lands are designated
for recreation, et cetera.

00:45:28.790 --> 00:45:31.970
The National Park
Service has less lands,

00:45:31.970 --> 00:45:34.610
although they have a great
deal of lands in the California

00:45:34.610 --> 00:45:35.110
desert.

00:45:35.110 --> 00:45:39.470
The National Park Service has
a more conservation-focused

00:45:39.470 --> 00:45:43.820
mission, and that mission is
to protect those resources that

00:45:43.820 --> 00:45:45.964
exist there in perpetuity.

00:45:45.964 --> 00:45:47.380
There are other
land managers that

00:45:47.380 --> 00:45:49.100
are not in the
Department of Interior,

00:45:49.100 --> 00:45:51.590
like the Forest
Service, for example,

00:45:51.590 --> 00:45:54.010
which is in the
Department of Agriculture.

00:45:54.010 --> 00:45:57.040
And there's also the
Department of Defense,

00:45:57.040 --> 00:45:59.420
which owns something like
3 million acres of land

00:45:59.420 --> 00:46:00.590
in the California desert.

00:46:00.590 --> 00:46:05.560
So there's a lot of different
types of designations.

00:46:05.560 --> 00:46:07.650
The national monuments
that I discussed-- Sand

00:46:07.650 --> 00:46:10.030
to Snow and Mojave
Trails-- those

00:46:10.030 --> 00:46:13.280
are both owned by the
Bureau of Land Management,

00:46:13.280 --> 00:46:15.430
and they are being
protected for the protection

00:46:15.430 --> 00:46:17.080
of their resources.

00:46:17.080 --> 00:46:20.870
Castle Mountains is owned by
the National Park Service,

00:46:20.870 --> 00:46:24.200
and is going to be protected in
perpetuity for the protection

00:46:24.200 --> 00:46:24.990
of its resources.

00:46:24.990 --> 00:46:29.490
So in both cases, they
have extremely high levels

00:46:29.490 --> 00:46:30.435
of protection.

00:46:30.435 --> 00:46:31.810
AUDIENCE: I was
wondering how you

00:46:31.810 --> 00:46:35.000
think about the future
of having people being

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:37.600
able to camp in these preserves
and in these national parks,

00:46:37.600 --> 00:46:40.270
but also making sure that
they aren't destroying them

00:46:40.270 --> 00:46:43.000
at the same time, and what you
think tourism in that sense

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:45.810
will be as we go on.

00:46:45.810 --> 00:46:48.320
DAVID LAMFROM: I think that's
a really important question.

00:46:48.320 --> 00:46:51.810
And it's a tough
thing for-- I think

00:46:51.810 --> 00:46:54.060
that it's really easy to
look at it in this binary way

00:46:54.060 --> 00:46:57.010
where the amount of people
who use something directly

00:46:57.010 --> 00:47:02.072
correlates to the intensity
to which it is harmed.

00:47:02.072 --> 00:47:04.030
I don't think that that's
necessarily the case.

00:47:04.030 --> 00:47:07.790
And I think in many cases,
the more a person steps

00:47:07.790 --> 00:47:10.490
foot on a place, the
softer their foot

00:47:10.490 --> 00:47:14.270
becomes, because they
come to care about it.

00:47:14.270 --> 00:47:15.780
They come to understand it.

00:47:15.780 --> 00:47:19.825
And so I don't think that it's
really about the specific use.

00:47:19.825 --> 00:47:24.540
I think it's about people
being open to understanding

00:47:24.540 --> 00:47:29.440
what a place is, and why it
matters, and who it's for.

00:47:29.440 --> 00:47:33.480
And the answer to who
it's for is for everybody,

00:47:33.480 --> 00:47:35.750
and that matters.

00:47:35.750 --> 00:47:39.900
And it's hard sometimes to
have the perspective of time

00:47:39.900 --> 00:47:43.880
to think about who came before
and who will come after.

00:47:43.880 --> 00:47:48.275
But I think it's a humble
and important thing for us

00:47:48.275 --> 00:47:48.900
to think about.

00:47:48.900 --> 00:47:54.540
And I think that ultimately,
we have to show people,

00:47:54.540 --> 00:47:58.170
and not in a judgey way, or not
in a restrictive, necessarily,

00:47:58.170 --> 00:47:59.180
way.

00:47:59.180 --> 00:48:01.340
But just about being-- I
think that there's nothing

00:48:01.340 --> 00:48:04.550
more compelling to me than
people who love things.

00:48:04.550 --> 00:48:06.510
And so if we have
genuine stewards

00:48:06.510 --> 00:48:08.240
in places who care
about places, I

00:48:08.240 --> 00:48:11.550
think we will have those places.

00:48:11.550 --> 00:48:13.810
AUDIENCE: And maybe
what you have observed

00:48:13.810 --> 00:48:16.490
and what you are
observing currently,

00:48:16.490 --> 00:48:19.810
and maybe what would be
your hopes for the future,

00:48:19.810 --> 00:48:26.520
and the two sides of
it-- how technology

00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:31.830
gets to separate
people from nature,

00:48:31.830 --> 00:48:37.400
and as you said, what
we don't directly know,

00:48:37.400 --> 00:48:43.290
and I think that we don't
directly engage with.

00:48:43.290 --> 00:48:47.570
Maybe we don't really
feel the need to protect.

00:48:47.570 --> 00:48:51.870
And the other side--
how technology may help

00:48:51.870 --> 00:48:54.900
to-- completely the opposite.

00:48:54.900 --> 00:48:57.814
We establish that connection.

00:48:57.814 --> 00:49:00.230
DAVID LAMFROM: I think that's
a really wonderful question,

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:02.610
and I think there's
a lot of answers.

00:49:02.610 --> 00:49:05.170
There's a lot of ways that
we could discuss this.

00:49:05.170 --> 00:49:10.260
But there's a couple of, I
think, really immediate points.

00:49:10.260 --> 00:49:16.420
One is it's an incredibly
privileged position

00:49:16.420 --> 00:49:22.330
to have the Earth sustain you,
to have food, to have water,

00:49:22.330 --> 00:49:25.200
to have everything
you need, and then

00:49:25.200 --> 00:49:27.580
to say I don't need nature.

00:49:27.580 --> 00:49:31.280
It's a very privileged
place to be.

00:49:31.280 --> 00:49:37.610
And I don't think it's
about people having

00:49:37.610 --> 00:49:40.330
to reconnect to
nature, or that people

00:49:40.330 --> 00:49:42.630
have disassociated from nature.

00:49:42.630 --> 00:49:49.310
I think it's that continuum
that I was discussing before,

00:49:49.310 --> 00:49:55.190
which is if you think-- if we
all think back-- and some of us

00:49:55.190 --> 00:49:57.580
don't even have the privilege
of knowing-- I don't know--

00:49:57.580 --> 00:50:00.920
I can't go that far back
in my own family tree

00:50:00.920 --> 00:50:03.710
and know exactly what my
distant relatives did.

00:50:03.710 --> 00:50:05.360
I have no idea.

00:50:05.360 --> 00:50:09.480
But a couple generations ago,
we were all fundamentally

00:50:09.480 --> 00:50:11.670
connected to the land.

00:50:11.670 --> 00:50:15.270
And understanding who we
are and where we came from

00:50:15.270 --> 00:50:18.690
is a function of understanding
that we came from the land.

00:50:18.690 --> 00:50:20.640
And it's not about--
I think it's not

00:50:20.640 --> 00:50:25.590
about certain good Samaritans
showing folks, hey, let

00:50:25.590 --> 00:50:26.840
me show you how to be outside.

00:50:26.840 --> 00:50:27.798
Let me take you hiking.

00:50:27.798 --> 00:50:29.130
Let me teach you how to camp.

00:50:29.130 --> 00:50:33.210
It's about people
understanding themselves

00:50:33.210 --> 00:50:34.570
and where they come from.

00:50:34.570 --> 00:50:38.600
And I don't think every person
has to be an environmentalist.

00:50:38.600 --> 00:50:42.720
Or maybe every person doesn't
even enjoy being outside.

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:45.682
But I think that you
have to understand

00:50:45.682 --> 00:50:47.140
that you're on this
planet, and you

00:50:47.140 --> 00:50:48.650
have to understand
your place on it,

00:50:48.650 --> 00:50:53.200
and that you have a
profound privilege.

00:50:53.200 --> 00:50:56.610
We, at least, have this
incredible privilege.

00:50:56.610 --> 00:51:01.214
And part of that is being
respectful of that world.

00:51:01.214 --> 00:51:02.630
Now, when you think
about and talk

00:51:02.630 --> 00:51:06.550
about people who are
being disconnected

00:51:06.550 --> 00:51:13.740
due to technology-- so I just
think that because people-- I

00:51:13.740 --> 00:51:21.430
think people inherently
care about nature.

00:51:21.430 --> 00:51:25.680
Cat videos, animals-- people
are drawn instinctively,

00:51:25.680 --> 00:51:29.691
inherently to living creatures
on the Earth and to the Earth

00:51:29.691 --> 00:51:30.190
itself.

00:51:30.190 --> 00:51:32.910
And when people think about
themselves in beautiful places,

00:51:32.910 --> 00:51:35.240
they think about these places.

00:51:35.240 --> 00:51:37.690
It's a deep part of our ethos.

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:38.760
So we are connected.

00:51:38.760 --> 00:51:41.630
And so if I thought about
the lines of disconnection,

00:51:41.630 --> 00:51:44.610
I don't think that they're
really that far apart.

00:51:44.610 --> 00:51:48.110
And I frankly think
that technology can,

00:51:48.110 --> 00:51:50.530
if we're open to it-- I
think it's just about us

00:51:50.530 --> 00:51:52.690
being humbled.

00:51:52.690 --> 00:51:57.030
But I think if we're open to it,
technology can help us enjoy.

00:51:57.030 --> 00:52:01.510
I just saw today there was
an app, a Shazam for plants,

00:52:01.510 --> 00:52:05.330
where you take a
picture of a plant,

00:52:05.330 --> 00:52:07.770
and your phone is going to
tell you what that plant is.

00:52:10.440 --> 00:52:12.010
Because I still
use a typewriter,

00:52:12.010 --> 00:52:14.835
I wasn't the guy to invent that,
but I think that's awesome.

00:52:18.390 --> 00:52:23.820
It's easy to it's easy to
assume that we are very far,

00:52:23.820 --> 00:52:25.500
but we're not.

00:52:25.500 --> 00:52:26.620
We are here.

00:52:26.620 --> 00:52:28.900
We are a part of this
thing that's happening.

00:52:28.900 --> 00:52:35.150
And I think that really,
people have to take a moment.

00:52:35.150 --> 00:52:40.290
I think if you just really
calmly think about yourself

00:52:40.290 --> 00:52:42.020
and your place on
this Earth, you

00:52:42.020 --> 00:52:46.930
understand that you're connected
to all of these systems.

00:52:46.930 --> 00:52:49.050
We are plugged into the
natural world in way

00:52:49.050 --> 00:52:52.710
more ways than we're plugged
into the internet or our phones

00:52:52.710 --> 00:52:54.840
or any of these things.

00:52:54.840 --> 00:52:56.730
AUDIENCE: Are there
similar efforts

00:52:56.730 --> 00:53:00.110
to protect these deserts in
the other states in the west--

00:53:00.110 --> 00:53:06.200
in Arizona, Nevada,
Idaho, Wyoming, Utah,

00:53:06.200 --> 00:53:08.870
as you described in California?

00:53:08.870 --> 00:53:12.590
DAVID LAMFROM: There are
multiple and discreet efforts

00:53:12.590 --> 00:53:19.480
across the West in deserts and
in mountains to protect really,

00:53:19.480 --> 00:53:23.000
really precious places.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:25.800
I don't think that
there's anything--

00:53:25.800 --> 00:53:28.220
there is, I think, something
of this scale that's

00:53:28.220 --> 00:53:31.565
being thought about in the
state of Utah right now.

00:53:31.565 --> 00:53:33.190
Beyond that, I don't
think that there's

00:53:33.190 --> 00:53:36.200
anything of this magnitude
that has been envisioned.

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:38.520
And for me, what's
really remarkable

00:53:38.520 --> 00:53:43.430
is that we got there, that we
had the foresight to protect.

00:53:43.430 --> 00:53:48.380
That's a wild and vast land.

00:53:48.380 --> 00:53:51.410
But there are efforts.

00:53:51.410 --> 00:53:52.520
Efforts are ongoing.

00:53:52.520 --> 00:53:57.080
But the reality is
there's more to do.

00:53:57.080 --> 00:54:00.850
There's a tremendous amount of
really, really special places.

00:54:00.850 --> 00:54:04.900
But for these efforts
to actually work,

00:54:04.900 --> 00:54:06.590
they have to be authentic.

00:54:06.590 --> 00:54:10.500
And they have to be driven
by people who know the places

00:54:10.500 --> 00:54:11.930
and love the places.

00:54:11.930 --> 00:54:16.270
So I don't think that
conservation should not--

00:54:16.270 --> 00:54:17.720
that's not the right word.

00:54:17.720 --> 00:54:21.050
Conservation for its
own sake has value,

00:54:21.050 --> 00:54:27.140
but it's best when done
by people who love places

00:54:27.140 --> 00:54:28.680
to care for those places.

00:54:28.680 --> 00:54:35.280
Otherwise, it becomes
politics or a game.

00:54:35.280 --> 00:54:37.960
And that may take us farther
away from where we want to be,

00:54:37.960 --> 00:54:40.580
which is to really help
people understand these places

00:54:40.580 --> 00:54:42.077
and why they matter.

00:54:42.077 --> 00:54:43.660
MATT SHEETS: Thank
you so much, David.

00:54:43.660 --> 00:54:44.610
We really appreciate it.

00:54:44.610 --> 00:54:46.360
And thank you, everyone,
for coming today.

00:54:46.360 --> 00:54:50.294
[APPLAUSE]

